\destcalculus{} is based on simply typed lambda calculus featuring modal function types and modal boxing, in addition to unit ($[[①]]$), product ($\ottstype{\otimes}$) and sum ($\ottstype{\oplus}$) types. It is also equipped with the destination type $[[⌊ T ⌋ m]]$ and ampar type $[[S ⧔ T]]$ that have been previewed in~\cref{sec:working-with-dests} to represent DPS structure building. The core grammar of the language is presented in~\cref{fig:grammar}. We also provide commonly used syntactic sugar forms for terms in~\cref{fig:sterm}.\improvement{Go over this paragraph, it needs clean-up.}

Modes in \destcalculus{} have two axes\improvement{Remove the terminology “axes” for the modes. This terminology is specific to the Oxidizing Ocaml work and, while reasonably intuitive, isn't worth introducing for a single use.} --- multiplicity (i.e.\unsure{traditionally \emph{i.e.} and \emph{e.g.}, as any Latin phrase, are emphasised. I notice you don't emphasise them, and I presumably did at some point, so let's make sure it's uniform} linear/non-linear), and age control\improvement{Here and everywhere: “age” not “age control”. “Age control” is funny, but it doesn't make much sense in this context} --- and they take place on variable bindings in typing contexts $[[P]]$, and on function arrows, but are not part of the type itself.

We omit the mode annotation $[[m]]$ on function arrows and destinations when the mode in question is the multiplicative neutral element $[[¹ν]]$ of the mode semiring (in particular, a function arrow without annotation is linear by default). A function arrow with multiplicity $[[¹]]$ is equivalent to the linear arrow $\ottstype{\multimap}$ from~\cite{girard_linear_1995}.

\subsection{Age-control for bindings to prevent scope escape of destinations}\label{ssec:age-control}

The solution we chose to alleviate scope escape of destinations (detailed in~\cref{sec:scope-escape-dests}) is to track the age of destinations (as De-Brujin-like scope indices), and to set age-control restriction on the typing rule of destination-filling primitives.

Age is represented by a commutative semiring\improvement{You say “commutative semiring” a lot. But maybe it'll be relaxing to ponder that in reality, our semirings aren't really semirings at all: they don't have a $0$. Instead, just say “semiring” and be clear about your definition. The first occurrence should mention (possibly in a footnote) that semirings in this paper aren't assume to have a $0$ but are assumed to be commutative.}\info{(Yann) I think they call this ringoid in the Bernardy et al. paper on modalities}, where $[[ν]]$ indicates that a destination originates from the current scope, and $[[↑]]$ indicates that it originates from the scope just before. Finally, age $[[∞]]$ is introduced for variables standing in place of a non-age-controlled value. In particular, destinations can never have age $[[∞]]$; the main role of age $[[∞]]$ is thus to act as a proof that no destination can be part of the value.\info{I removed the bit about extending ages to variables because we, in fact, have no age (or multiplicity, or mod) variables.}

Semiring addition $\ottsmode{+}$ is used to find the age of a variable or destination that is used in two subterms of a program. Semiring multiplication $[[·]]$ corresponds to age composition, and is in fact an integer sum on scope indices.
$[[∞]]$ is absorbing for both addition and multiplication.
